==Culture==
{{main|Sociological and cultural aspects of autism}}
* [[Autism rights movement]] (ARM) &ndash; (also neurodiversity movement or anti-cure movement or autistic culture movement) is a social movement that encourages autistic people, their caregivers and society to adopt a position of neurodiversity, accepting autism as a variation in functioning rather than a mental disorder to be cured.
* [[Autistic art]] &ndash; art created by autistic artists or art which captures or conveys a variety of autistic experiences or demeanor.
* [[Neurodiversity]] &ndash;
* [[Neurotypical]] &ndash; (or NT) is a term that was coined in the autistic community as a label for people who are not on the autism spectrum: specifically, neurotypical people have neurological development and states that are consistent with what most people would perceive as normal, particularly with respect to their ability to process linguistic information and social cues.
* [[Sociological and cultural aspects of autism]] &ndash; come into play with recognition of autism, approaches to its support services and therapies, and how autism affects how we define personhood.

