==Therapies and interventions==
{{main|Autism therapies}}
* [[Applied behavior analysis]] (ABA) &ndash; a science that involves using modern behavioral learning theory to modify behaviors.
* [[Chelation therapy]] &ndash; the administration of chelating agents to remove heavy metals from the body.
* [[Clomipramine]] &ndash; (trademarked as Anafranil) is a tricyclic antidepressant (TCA).
* [[Craniosacral therapy]] &ndash; (also called CST, also spelled Cranial Sacral bodywork or therapy) is an alternative medicine therapy used by physiotherapists, osteopaths, massage therapists, naturopaths, and chiropractors.
* [[Ethical challenges to autism treatment]] &ndash;
* [[Floortime]] &ndash; a developmental intervention involving meeting a child at his or her current developmental level, and challenging them to move up the hierarchy of milestones outlined in the DIR Model.
* [[Fluvoxamine]] &ndash; (brand name Luvox) is an antidepressant which functions as a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI).
* [[Gluten-free, casein-free diet]] &ndash; ) or gluten-free dairy-free diet (GFDF diet) eliminates dietary intake of the naturally occurring proteins gluten (found most often in wheat, barley, rye, and commercially available oats), and casein (found most often in milk and dairy products).
* [[Haloperidol]] &ndash; a typical antipsychotic.
* [[Hyperbaric oxygen therapy]] &ndash;
* [[Hug machine]] &ndash; hug box, a squeeze machine, or a squeeze box, is a deep-pressure device designed to calm hyper-sensitive persons, usually individuals with autism spectrum disorders.
* [[Lovaas technique]] &ndash;
* [[Pivotal response therapy]] (PRT) &ndash; also referred to as pivotal response treatment or pivotal response training, is a behavioral intervention therapy for autism.
* [[The P.L.A.Y. Project]] &ndash;
* [[Relationship Development Intervention]] (RDI) &ndash; a trademarked proprietary treatment program for autism spectrum disorders (ASD), based on the belief that the development of dynamic intelligence is the key to improving the quality of life for individuals with autism.
* [[Risperidone]] &ndash; (Risperdal, and generics) is a second-generation or atypical antipsychotic.
* [[Secretin]] &ndash; a hormone that controls the secretions into the duodenum, and also separately, water homeostasis throughout the body.
* [[Son-Rise]] &ndash;
* [[Speech therapy]] &ndash;
* [[TEACCH]] &ndash;
* [[Treatment and education of autistic and related communication handicapped children]] &ndash;
* [[Vitamin B12]] &ndash; vitamin B-12, also called cobalamin, is a water-soluble vitamin with a key role in the normal functioning of the brain and nervous system, and for the formation of blood.

==Possibly associated conditions==
{{main|Conditions comorbid to autism spectrum disorders}}

These are conditions that people on the autism spectrum may suffer from more often than is typical.
* [[Alexithymia]] &ndash; a term coined by psychotherapist Peter Sifneos in 1973 to describe a state of deficiency in understanding, processing, or describing emotions.
* [[Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder]] (ADHD)
* [[Autistic enterocolitis]] &ndash; other studies have explicitly refuted its existence.
* [[Clinical depression]] &ndash;
* [[Coeliac disease]] &ndash; spelled celiac disease in North America and often celiac sprue) is an autoimmune disorder of the small intestine that occurs in genetically predisposed people of all ages from middle infancy onward.
* [[Communication disorder]] &ndash; a speech and language disorder which refers to problems in communication and in related areas such as oral motor function.
* [[Crohn's disease]] (MAP) &ndash; which causes a similar disease, Johne's disease, in cattle.
* [[Deafness]] &ndash; or hearing impairment, is a partial or total inability to hear where the ability would usually be expected.
* [[Dyscalculia]] &ndash; a specific learning disability involving innate difficulty in learning or comprehending arithmetic.
* [[Dysgraphia]] &ndash; a deficiency in the ability to write primarily in terms of handwriting, but also in terms of coherence.
* [[Dyslexia]] &ndash; a very broad term defining a learning disability that impairs a person's fluency or comprehension accuracy in being able to read, and which can manifest itself as a difficulty with phonological awareness, phonological decoding, orthographic coding, auditory short-term memory, or rapid naming.
* [[Dyspraxia]] &ndash;
* [[Echolalia]] &ndash; the automatic repetition of vocalizations made by another person.
* [[Erotophobia]] &ndash; a term coined by a number of researchers in the late 1970s and early 1980s to describe one pole on a continuum of attitudes and beliefs about sexuality.
* [[Hyperlexia]] &ndash; the precocious ability to read words without prior training in learning to read typically before the age of 5.
* [[Inflammatory bowel disease]] (IBD) &ndash; a group of inflammatory conditions of the colon and small intestine.
* [[Mental retardation]] (MR) &ndash; a generalized disorder appearing before adulthood, characterized by significantly impaired cognitive functioning and deficits in two or more adaptive behaviors.
* [[Multiple-complex Developmental Disorder]] &ndash;
* [[Multisystem Developmental Disorder]] &ndash;
* [[Nonverbal learning disorder]] &ndash; or nonverbal learning disability (NLD or NVLD) is a condition characterized by a significant discrepancy between higher verbal and lower motor, Theory_of_multiple_intelligences#Visual-spatial|visuo-spatial, and social skills on an IQ test.
* [[Obsessive Compulsive Disorder]] &ndash;
* [[Picture thinking]] &ndash;
* [[Pyroluria]] &ndash;
* [[Semantic pragmatic disorder]] &ndash;
* [[Sensory integration dysfunction]] &ndash; a disorder characterized by a sensory integration deficit.
* [[Sensory defensiveness]] &ndash; a condition defined as having "a tendency to react negatively or with alarm to sensory input which is generally considered harmless or non-irritating" to neurotypical persons.
* [[Sensory overload]] &ndash; related to Cognitive load in general, is a condition where one or more of the senses are strained and it becomes difficult to focus on the task at hand.
* [[Social alienation]] &ndash; estrangement, division, or distancing of people from each other, or of people from what is important or meaningful to them, or of a person from their own sense of self.

